Next, because switching rate alone is not high enough to explain the distance shortening, we hypothesize that this effect is caused by DNA damage, which in this strain can include either SSB or DBS. One possibility would be that the observed proximity in inter-loci distance is associated with DSB. In other words, whenever a DSB occurs, HMLα-MAT proximity is induced. To explore this option, we repeated our analysis, namely, zeroing the inter-loci distances of a subset of the population that corresponds to the fraction of cells exhibiting DSB, and checking whether the proximity-dip shown in Fig. 3E is explainable this way. Because the DSB rate is not directly known, we estimate it using a strain without FROS (based on the results in Fig. 2). In that strain, switching was ~ 2.8-fold higher compared to the strain with FROS. Assuming that most DSBs correspond to a switching event in the strain without FROS15 we estimate a DSB rate of approximately 10% (calculated as ~ 2.8\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:\times\:$$\end{document}3.5%) at time points 30 and 60 min. Still, a significant proximity between the loci remains unexplained in the population (Fig. 4A; turquoise line). Since most of the population experienced DNA damage, either SSB or DSB, according to our qPCR results, we finally conclude that the HMLα-MAT proximity might be caused both by SSB and DSB.

